crops.description: A fine-flavored South African papaya, pollinized by a plant from the Sandwich Islands.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washington, D. C.
crops.description: A large tropical tree of the Brazilian forests, with rigid leathery oblong leaves 3 to 5 inches long and shining green above. The greenish, ovoid-cylindrical fruits, about 2 inches long, yield an oil known as Oiticica oil, that is used in the paint and varnish industry.

crops.presented_by: Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo
crops.description: A small papaya 312 by 412 inches, with very thin flesh which is highly acid and is used only in making preserves and syrups. The fruit is yellow when ripe with a spicy aromatic flavor and fragrance, but is never eaten fresh.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.experiment_name: A new type of rice developed near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, which develops abnormally large ears and is a heavy yielder.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul, Porto Alegre
crops.experiment_name: Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul.

crops.presented_by: G. S. Jamieson, Bureau of Chemistry and Soils
crops.description: For previous introduction and description see 106347.

The 'sausage tree' of eastern tropical Africa becomes 30 to 50 feet high, with rough ternate leaves made up of seven to nine elliptic-oblong leaflets; the large claret-colored flowers are in long spikes, and the blunt sausage-like fruits are 12 to 18 inches long.

crops.presented_by: F. H. Brunning Pty. Ltd., Melbourne
W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: A tropical shrub with thick leathery oval-elliptic dark-green leaves and small white flowers in large terminal cymes. It is native to Brazil.

crops.presented_by: W. A. Archer, Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: Garuru. A handsome tree with leathery elliptic leaves shining green above and 4 to 6 inches long and large yellow flowers. Native to sandy places in British Guiana.

crops.experiment_name: Common red pepper. A cultivated variety.

crops.description: Cuttings of a large tropical tree with opposite digitately 3- to 5-foliolate leathery leaves, large greenish flowers, and hard-shelled nuts with white edible kernels.
Cuttings from a small tree of rather straggly habit with golden-yellow flowers in loose racemes.
A cultivated watermelon collected at Bartica, on the Essequiba River.
Bulbs of cultivated plants collected at Mazaruni Station.
